<item>
            <title>[THRIFT-1606] Race condition in BoostThreadFactory.cpp</title>
                <link>https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/THRIFT-1606</link>
                <project id="12310800" key="THRIFT">Thrift</project>
                    <description>&lt;p&gt;During deployment, we noticed a bug inside the new (optional) boost thread replacement of pthread.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It moves the line:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;    state_ = starting;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;from after the creation of the boost::thread to immediately before it.  The bug was that one of the first pieces of threadMain (the thread routine of the thread being created) is:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;  if (thread-&amp;gt;state_ != starting) &lt;/p&gt;
{
    return (void*)0;
  }

&lt;p&gt;So there was a race condition between the line that set state_ to &quot;starting&quot;, and the line that checked to make sure that it was &quot;starting&quot;.  That ended meaning that sometimes calling &quot;start()&quot; would not result in the thread&apos;s runnable being called.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Testing: this was tested in production, but NOT with thrift test suite (however I believe ./configure --enable_boostthreads and testing will cover this)&lt;/p&gt;</description>
                <environment>&lt;p&gt;Debian, Redhat, Windows&lt;/p&gt;</environment>
